---
import BaseLayout from "../layouts/BaseLayout.astro";
---
<BaseLayout title="Methodology | ITR Atlas">
  <article class="prose">
    <h1>Methodology</h1>

    <h2>What ITR measures</h2>
    <p>Information transfer rate (ITR) estimates how many bits per second a user can communicate
       through an interface. For discrete selection it is usually computed with the
       <strong>Wolpaw formula</strong> for bits per selection:</p>
    <pre class="mono">B = log2(N) + P*log2(P) + (1-P)*log2((1-P)/(N-1))</pre>
    <p>multiplied by selections per second. Here <em>N</em> is the number of targets and
       <em>P</em> is accuracy.</p>

    <h2>Why a single number is often misleading</h2>
    <p>The Wolpaw ITR is the channel capacity of an <em>idealized</em> discrete channel. It assumes
       that every target is equally likely (a uniform prior), errors are spread evenly over the other
       targets (symmetric and memoryless), selection time is fixed, and no time is spent correcting
       mistakes. Under those assumptions, the formula above is exact. For real interfaces it is
       better read as an <strong>upper bound</strong>, because the assumptions fail in ordinary use.
       The overestimate grows with both accuracy and the number of symbols
       (<a href="https://doi.org/10.1371/journal.pone.0078432">Speier, Arnold &amp; Pouratian 2013</a>;
       <a href="https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/23448963/">Yuan et al. 2013</a>).</p>
    <p>Other estimators remove specific assumptions. Confusion-matrix mutual information drops the
       symmetric-error assumption
       (<a href="https://www.yumpu.com/en/document/view/33702582/statistical-modelling-issues-for-the-adaptive-brain-interface">Nykopp 2001</a>;
       <a href="https://archive-ouverte.unige.ch/unige:47811">Kronegg et al. 2005</a>). A language
       model drops the uniform-prior assumption (Speier and colleagues, above). A continuous control
       channel needs a throughput model rather than a discrete-selection count. The entries in this
       atlas differ mainly in which assumption they break and which replacement measure is defensible.</p>

    <h2>The predictor is part of the measurement</h2>
    <p>A bits figure depends on the <em>predictor</em> assumed at the receiving end, not only on the
       physical or neural channel. If a language model can reconstruct some redundancy from context,
       that redundancy did not need to cross the interface. A stronger predictor therefore gives a
       lower information rate. To keep entries comparable, the predictor has to stay
       <strong>constant across every entry</strong>. We use a conservative full-context bound of about
       <strong>1 bit per character</strong> for English text throughout.
       Shannon's prediction experiments first bracketed printed English between 0.6 and 1.3 bits/char
       (<a href="https://ieeexplore.ieee.org/document/6773263">Shannon 1951</a>). Modern estimates
       land just above our working value: about <strong>1.12 bits/char</strong> by extrapolating
       neural language models to unlimited data
       (<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC7512401/">Takahira et al. 2016</a>) and
       about <strong>1.22 bits/char</strong> in a large-scale replication of Shannon's guessing game
       (<a href="https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC7514546/">Ren et al. 2020</a>). So 1
       bit/char is a deliberate, slightly conservative floor. The per-word figure is not a separate
       measurement. Text-entry rates define one word as five characters
       (<a href="https://doi.org/10.1145/642611.642632">Soukoreff &amp; MacKenzie 2003</a>), the same
       convention behind the words-per-minute figures in this atlas, so the bound is equivalently
       <strong>5 bits per word</strong>.</p>
    <p>Speech shows the problem plainly. A widely cited cross-language study reports an average
       information rate of <strong>~39 bits/second</strong> for spoken language
       (<a href="https://www.science.org/doi/10.1126/sciadv.aaw2594">Coupé et al. 2019</a>). That
       study set out to compare encoding efficiency <em>across</em> 17 languages, and for that
       purpose it uses syllable-level entropy estimated from local context. That estimator is
       computable and comparable across languages with very different corpus resources. It also
       counts redundancy that a full-context predictor would resolve, so it measures a different
       quantity from the channel-net information this atlas tracks. If we used ~39 bps here, speech
       would be evaluated with a different predictor from QWERTY, Morse, and the BCI spellers.</p>
    <p>With the predictor held fixed, the speech estimate comes back into line. When conversational
       English is measured with a large language model as the predictor, the same full-context
       standard we apply to text, it
       lands at <strong>~13 bits/second</strong>
       (<a href="https://arxiv.org/abs/2403.08890">Bergey &amp; DeDeo 2024</a>), matching our text
       entries (≈150 wpm × 5 bits/word). Spoken and written English carry essentially the same net
       information when they are evaluated with the same predictor. The 3× spread is an estimator
       difference, not a modality difference, which is why this atlas keeps one predictor across
       entries.</p>

    <h2>What we rank on: the strictest upper bound</h2>
    <p>Most of these measures are <strong>upper bounds</strong> on what a channel can carry: Fitts'
       index of difficulty, the Wolpaw bits-per-selection, log₂(N), and the Nuyujukian achieved
       bitrate each cap the rate under their own idealizing assumptions. The one exception is the
       Shannon realized-text figure, which counts the information the output actually delivers as
       English under a fixed predictor. Because one entry can admit several of these, we report the
       <strong>strictest (smallest)</strong> of them as the headline — the best-supported estimate of
       what the interface really achieves — and a score selector on the home page lets you view any
       single method across entries instead. These are the methods an entry can be scored by:</p>
    <ul>
      <li><strong>The output is language</strong> → character-entropy throughput
         (characters/min × ~1 bit/char), the same full-context Shannon predictor used for QWERTY
         everywhere. This covers keyboards, Morse, eye-typing, and the BCI spellers (P300, SSVEP,
         c-VEP), because all of them emit English text.</li>
      <li><strong>The channel is continuous cursor motion</strong> → Fitts throughput,
         <strong>log₂(A/W + 1)</strong> per movement divided by movement time, computed from the
         interface's own geometry. This covers the mouse, trackball, stylus, tongue drive, gaze
         pointing, and the cursor BCIs. Accuracy is folded in the way Fitts handles it: via
         the <em>effective</em> width W<sub>e</sub> = 4.133·SD of the movement endpoints (ISO 9241-9),
         which discounts the information per movement to the precision actually achieved, so there is
         no separate error term and you cannot game it by moving fast and missing. Where a source
         publishes no endpoint scatter (e.g. the sensorimotor-rhythm cursor), we say so and fall back
         to a plain completion-rate discount.</li>
      <li><strong>The output is a closed, non-language command set</strong> → Wolpaw/log₂(N) over the
         real action set, discounted by accuracy. There is no language predictor to apply, so the
         target set itself is the output.</li>
    </ul>
    <p>The strictest-bound rule settles cursor tasks that can be read more than one way. Fitts is
       usually lower because it measures the movement the user actually made. A Wolpaw-style
       target-acquisition estimate can be lower when the task has only a small set of cued endpoints;
       then it wins the strictest-min and the Fitts derivation is kept as a check. The
       sensorimotor-rhythm cursor is the current example: eight cued targets give a Wolpaw estimate
       below the geometry-based Fitts estimate.</p>
    <p>Raw-channel counts — Wolpaw, log₂(N), achieved-bitrate, Webgrid BPS, c-VEP discrimination —
       are upper bounds on task-specific channels and sit alongside the others as selectable methods.
       They rarely win the strictest-min, by design: log₂(N) over a decoder alphabet whose size is a
       knob inflates without limit. Neuralink's Webgrid carves a continuous cursor into 900 cells
       (~9.8 bits/selection); make the grid denser and the number rises while the control is
       unchanged. EEG2Code shows the same at a larger scale: it discriminates <strong>500,000</strong>
       random codes at ~100% from 2 s of EEG, log₂(500,000) ≈ 19 bits per selection, 11.7 bits/s, and
       the authors themselves flag a "ceiling effect" where those bits are not all usable as control
       commands (<a href="https://doi.org/10.1371/journal.pone.0221909">Nagel &amp; Spüler 2019</a>). A
       speller that emits English but is credited log₂(40) per letter is being evaluated with a
       different predictor than QWERTY held to 1 bit/char — a loose bound the strictest-min discards
       in favor of the realized-text figure. That is the same apples-to-oranges mismatch we reject for
       speech.</p>
    <p>This ranking rule also keeps the taxonomy from doing too much work. A cursor traversing space
       (Fitts), a frequency or code classifier (SSVEP, c-VEP), and covert attention with no movement
       at all (P300) can carry different secondary metric labels without changing the ranked measure. We
       therefore do not have to decide whether covert attention "really" obeys Fitts' law. As a
       check on the Fitts side, the able-bodied ~10 BPS reported on Webgrid reduces by this method to
       ~4.1 bits/s, close to the independently measured throughput of a physical mouse (~4.5 bits/s).</p>
    <p>None of the current speller entries are closed non-language command sets; every speller here
       types English.</p>

    <h2>How we pick the headline number</h2>
    <ol>
      <li>Compute every applicable method from the paper's inputs — the paper's own calculation where
         it exists and is sound, otherwise a modality-appropriate recomputation.</li>
      <li>Rank the entry on the <strong>strictest (smallest)</strong> of the figures that are valid
         for its task; the Shannon realized-text figure competes on equal footing with the bounds.</li>
      <li>Keep the looser figures as secondary derivations on the entry page, reachable through the
         score selector.</li>
    </ol>

    <h2>Provenance labels</h2>
    <ul>
      <li><strong>Author-reported · reproduced</strong>: we recomputed the number from the paper's stated inputs and matched it.</li>
      <li><strong>Author-reported · not reproduced</strong>: the paper gives a number but doesn't expose enough to recompute it.</li>
      <li><strong>Recomputed</strong>: no comparable ITR in the paper; we computed one from its inputs.</li>
    </ul>
  </article>
</BaseLayout>

